>
  <p>
    A star rating is an average, and averages are famously good at hiding the
    truth. The headline number is the first thing you see and the least
    informative thing on the page. Here's what to look at instead.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Volume: how many people actually voted</h2>
  <p>
    This is the big one. A 4.8-star average from 40 reviews and a 4.6-star average
    from 12,000 are not close calls — the second product is dramatically more
    proven. With 40 reviews, a handful of friends, a small paid batch, or plain
    luck can move the average half a star. With 12,000, the rating has been
    stress-tested by thousands of real households across years of use.
  </p>
  <p>
    Statisticians call this a confidence problem: small samples are noisy, and a
    small sample of glowing reviews should <em>lower</em> your confidence, not
    raise it. A useful mental rule — if a product has fewer than a few hundred
    reviews, treat its rating as a rough guess, not a verdict.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Distribution: what's hiding behind the average</h2>
  <p>
    A 4.0 average can mean two completely different things. It might be a product
    almost everyone rates a solid four — consistent, dependable, no surprises. Or
    it might be a product half of buyers love (five stars) and a third quietly
    hate (one star), averaging out to the same 4.0. That second product is a
    gamble; the average erases the risk.
  </p>
  <p>
    So look at the bars, not just the number. The percentage of one- and two-star
    reviews is often more revealing than the average itself. A high share of
    one-star reviews on a product with an otherwise good average is a red flag that
    something fails for a meaningful minority of people — a defect, a sizing issue,
    a durability problem. Read those low reviews and check whether the same
    complaint keeps recurring.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Recency: is it still the same product?</h2>
  <p>
    Manufacturers change suppliers, cut costs, and revise designs while keeping the
    same listing — and all the old five-star reviews come along for the ride. A
    product can carry a 4.7 lifetime average while its <em>last three months</em>
    of reviews have collapsed to 3.5 because the current batch is worse.
  </p>
  <p>
    Always sort by most recent and read what buyers are saying now. If recent
    reviews trend well below the lifetime average, believe the recent ones — you're
    buying today's product, not the one that earned the old stars.
  </p>

  <h2>Putting it together</h2>
  <p>
    Next time you're comparing two products, don't stop at the star number. Ask:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>How many reviews is that average built on?</strong> More is more trustworthy.</li>
    <li><strong>What does the distribution look like?</strong> Watch the one-star share.</li>
    <li><strong>What are people saying in the last few months?</strong> Recent beats lifetime.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do that, and the 4.8-with-40-reviews product often loses to the 4.6 with
    thousands behind it — which is exactly the call the raw star number would have
    talked you out of.
  </p>

  <h2>Why our scores weight this automatically</h2>
  <p>
    Reading volume, distribution, and recency for every product in a category is
    tedious — so we built it into the <a href="/how-we-rate/">Insider Score</a>.
    Verified customer ratings form the 50% foundation, but we layer <strong>review
    volume and consistency (20%)</strong> on top, discounting thinly-reviewed
    products and flagging ones whose recent reviews have slipped. The result is a
    single number that already accounts for the things a bare star average leaves
    out.
  </p>
